{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}} {{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Five Star Krishna | image = | caption = Five Star | birth_name = Krishnakumar Ramakumar | birth_date =18/10 | birth_place = Chennai, India | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = [[Film actor]] [[Advertisement]] [[Film Maker]] | spouse = Gowri Krishnakumar | website = | imagesize = 180px | othername = Five Star Krishna | yearsactive = 2002–present | notable role = }}
'''Krishnakumar Ramakumar''', also credited as '''Five Star Krishna''', is an Indian [[film actor]] who has appeared in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] films in supporting roles. He made his debut in [[Mani Ratnam]]'s production ''[[Five Star (film)|Five Star]]'' (2002), before playing pivotal roles in ''[[Arinthum Ariyamalum]]'' and ''[[Saravana]]''.
==Career== Krishna, who had previously apprenticed under [[Rajiv Menon]] as an assistant director, was signed on by [[Susi Ganesan]] to appear in a leading role in ''[[Five Star (film)|Five Star]]'', produced by [[Mani Ratnam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chennaionline.com/location/5star.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021119014118/http://www.chennaionline.com/location/5star.asp|dead-url=yes|archive-date=19 November 2002|title=Five Star|publisher=|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chennaionline.com/interviews/krishnakumar.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030225112924/http://www.chennaionline.com/interviews/krishnakumar.asp|dead-url=yes|archive-date=25 February 2003|title=5 Star-Krishna Kumar|publisher=|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Portraying a runaway husband, he won rave reviews with The Hindu's critic noting "there are scenes where he could have underplayed his emotions a little&nbsp;— but surely the young man has talent".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fr/2002/10/11/stories/2002101101170200.htm|title=The Hindu : Five Star|publisher=}}</ref> After winning good reviews for his performance in ''Five Star'', Krishna followed it up playing supporting roles in films including [[Cheran (director)|Cheran]]'s ''[[Autograph (2004 film)|Autograph]]'' and as a student leader in [[Mani Ratnam]]'s ''[[Aaytha Ezhuthu]]'', while also appearing as Dhanush's brother in the romantic comedy, ''[[Thiruda Thirudi]]''. He has since then notably appeared in projects directed by [[Vishnuvardhan (director)|Vishnuvardhan]], featuring in four consecutive ventures. He has balanced appearances in films alongside his advertisement agency.
In 2008, it was reported that he was set to direct a gangster film titled ''Madras'' starring Vishnuvardhan's brother [[Kreshna]] in the lead role, though the project did not materialise after a spat with the producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/just-arrived/article471135.ece|title=Just arrived|author=sudhish kamath|work=The Hindu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-04-04/news-interviews/28042245_1_alibaba-krishna-comedy|title=Krishna's acting hues|work=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/42959.html|title=Krishna to direct Krishna|publisher=}}</ref> Krishna has directed a commercial advertisement featuring [[Kamal Haasan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/kamal-to-act-in-a-commercial-advertisement-to-raise-funds-for-treatment-of-aids-patients-tamil-news-142702.html|title=Kamal to do it for the first time to help AIDS patients|publisher=}}</ref>
